arge enough to motivate a fix for it.*

Boom and Supersonic Flight

*There=E2=80=99s a lot of attention in Silicon Valley on Boom, a startup tr=
ying to build supersonic aircraft. It seems like the news is kind of pessim=
istic around that: you reported ( https://theaircurrent.com/aircraft-develo=
pment/boom-taps-trio-to-develop-an-engine-for-supersonic-overture/ ) they c=
an=E2=80=99t get one of the big engine suppliers to support them, so they=
=E2=80=99re trying to work with smaller suppliers.*

*One, what=E2=80=99s going on there, and two, why is no one else trying to =
do supersonic flight? Is it just the sense that no one=E2=80=99s going to p=
ay for it? I mean, you see this United purchase. They=E2=80=99re buying a b=
unch of relatively slow aircraft, right? As someone in Taiwan, believe me, =
I=E2=80=99m very invested in and interested in faster flights. Give me an o=
verview of like why are we stuck with 600 miles per hour or whatever it is?=
*

*JO:* I think you have to look at this from, again, a strategic perspective=
. Boom has come along, and I think supersonic fascinates people, because th=
ey want to go fast. They love the idea of zipping over time zones, and arri=
ving before you left, and all the glamour and sex appeal that comes along w=
ith that, and it is a sexy, sexy market. The problem is the economics are r=
eally tough. Going fast requires a lot of fuel, requires heavy maintenance =
on engines. It requires a lot of CO2, depending on what you=E2=80=99re putt=
ing in the tank.

Where Boom is right now, they=E2=80=99ve gotten to a point that they=E2=80=
=99ve got a manufacturing plant that they=E2=80=99re planning for North Car=
olina. They now have an engine supplier. They don=E2=80=99t have it with a =
traditional provider like Pratt, Rolls Royce and GE. But what they do have =
is working with a smaller organization called Florida Turbine Technologies,=
 which does small engines for things like cruise missiles and attritable ai=
rcraft. And those are very small, low thrust engines. So, this is a big lea=
p for them to go in this direction and Boom is actually taking on a lot of =
their responsibility of designing this engine as well. And that comes with =
the price tag that goes up by billions as a result of it, for this whole en=
deavor on top of the very large multi-billion dollar price tag to just buil=
d the aircraft.

I think the one thing that is really important here to remember is that sup=
ersonic is inherently 180 degrees opposed to all of the other strategic for=
ces within the airline industry. We talked about scarcity in terms of resou=
rces, in terms of fuel, in terms of pilots.

*Right. The whole thing of United buying a bunch of wide bodies is they nee=
d to maximize the number of people they carry in one plane. Well, supersoni=
c jets are small and yeah, so that makes total sense. It=E2=80=99s the exac=
t opposite.*

*JO:* So, the airline industry since the late =E2=80=9950s, we got to the 7=
07s and the DC8s, the first jetliners and went from higher, faster, farther=
 to faster, better, cheaper. And that has been the trend. And so as long as=
 the dynamics are that airlines are competing on cost =E2=80=94 I mean, the=
y would love to raise their prices and they have been able to because of th=
e, again, scarcity of capacity and the demand has grown and outstripped the=
 capacity of the system to accommodate it, so the prices come up and they l=
ove it. They=E2=80=99re back at pre pandemic revenues. It=E2=80=99s been gr=
eat. A problem is that comes with a whole other host of high costs and prob=
lems when your airline tips over.

Against that, you=E2=80=99ve got this reality where, there=E2=80=99s a real=
ly illuminating thing that happened in the early 2000s, pre-9/11. Boeing ac=
tually looked at a supersonic, or just barely supersonic airplane. It was a=
ctually mach 0.98. So, 98% of the speed of sound.

*Yeah, the Sonic Cruiser?*

*JO:* Yep. Exactly. One of the big benefits of that, when we talk about cre=
w scarcity, you actually could fly at a certain distance and actually requi=
re one less crew member because you were going fast enough to get in under =
the work rules. You=E2=80=99d actually get there in a time where you wouldn=
=E2=80=99t need the extra crew member. So, there was a savings there, but i=
t would end up burning about the same amount of fuel as an airplane built i=
n 1985. The airlines said, =E2=80=9CNo, no, no, we don=E2=80=99t want that.=
 We want to slow down, we need you to focus on the Dreamliner.=E2=80=9D But=
 one thing that they never realized was that Concord, when it flew from the=
 =E2=80=9970s to the early 2000s, what happened was you never had two diffe=
rent airlines flying on the same route.

*We never really knew how low the price could get, because there was no com=
petition.*

*JO:* Exactly. Yeah, exactly. So, if you want to justify the business case,=
 what ends up happening is you have to have airlines on the same route. If =
you put two Sonic Cruisers on the same route, what ends up happening is the=
y end up competing against each other to get the premium passenger paying f=
or speed. And then, =E2=80=9COh, by the way, all the wide body aircraft, sl=
ow pokey wide bodies, are going even lower to keep those aircraft running.=
=E2=80=9D And so what Boeing found was that you take a city pair like New Y=
ork to London and you actually take money out of it by introducing these ai=
rplanes, it=E2=80=99s actually a net loser.

*Interesting. So, it=E2=80=99s a great consumer benefit, but it just doesn=
=E2=80=99t work for the airlines. That makes sense.*

*JO:* That=E2=80=99s the dynamic that Boom fundamentally faces.

*So Boom doesn=E2=80=99t just need to make the aircraft, and they don=E2=80=
=99t just need to make the engine. It sounds like they need to make an airl=
ine too. It has to be almost fully integrated from the ground up to support=
